<!--
  offers-master.md.example — TEMPLATE for THE single canonical scored map of every offer.
  The LM agent INSTANTIATES data/offers-master.md FROM THIS file at session start (only if the
  runtime file is absent — otherwise it MERGES new survivors into the live file; never overwrite
  history). NEVER edit this .example as if it were the live map.
  Candidate-AGNOSTIC scaffolding: holds OFFERS + METRICS only — NEVER the user's PII (that lives
  in the NotebookLM RAG / data/cv/base/gary-context.md).
  On create, stamp: "> Instantiated by the LM agent at session start (from offers-master.md.example) — {absolute date}."

  HOW THIS FILE WORKS
  - One canonical doc, persists across sessions. Every sweep from EVERY channel MERGES its
    survivors here after the two-way-fit gate — never scatter into dated/per-channel docs or
    leave results only in survivors.json / an agent reply. (MANDATORY: persist after each connection.)
  - Dedup per the candidate's preference (DATA in gary-context.md / NotebookLM). Common case: dedup ONLY by
    exact offer (same posting/URL), NOT by company — multiple roles from one company ALL stay as separate rows.
  - Score: 0–5 two-way-fit vs the candidate's role/skill map (data/cv/base/gary-context.md + RAG).
    Only ≥4.0 are "apply"; 3.5–3.9 are "review"; <3.5 collapse into a one-line "discard".
    COMP handling per the candidate's preference (DATA) — common case: informational, never a filter/penalty.
  - Status boxes:  [ ] = pending · [x] = applied / closed / skip · [~] = flag.
  - Region-locked lines (US/UK/EU/India/…-only, E-Verify/work-auth, hybrid/on-site elsewhere) are
    DELETED unless the offer explicitly offers visa sponsorship. Closed/expired = [x].
  - Row format:  - [ ] **{Company}** — {Role} — {score} — {url} — {channel} — {notes / status}
  - Apply the ≤1-week recency rule (posted within 7 days) unless the user widens the window.

  CHANNELS: A=LinkedIn EasyApply · B=Manual (GetOnBoard/Computrabajo/etc.) · C=LinkedIn-via-Gmail
            · D=Himalayas · (add more as boards are wired). One section per channel.
-->

